                    <marginalia_text> 
                        A wonderfull, &amp; outragious resolution of the Abydenians.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Scitè ille: Audaces nimio cogimur esse metu. Sed quantò profundiùs Publius? Heu, quàm est timendus, qui mori tutum putat?
                        Aut ille, quicunq[ue] dixit: Aliena[e] vita[e] est dominus, qui sua[e] est contemptor. Miri sunt, et horribiles virorum spiritus, ipsa 
                        iam desperatione efferatorum.
                    </marginalia_text> 
                    <person name="Publilius Syrus"/> <!--KS: 'Heu quam est timendus, qui mori tutum putat!' is one of Publilius' sententiae.-->
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                He [argues] expertly: we are forced to be too bold by fear. Yet how much more profoundly so was Publilius. Ah, how much should he be feared who 
                thinks dying is harmless! Or him, whoever it was who said: the person who disdains his own life is the master of that of another. Remarkable 
                and fearsome are the spirits of the men now made ferocious by desperation itself.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
